fields.description:
Auto scaling was designed to work in HA with the assumption that the service would only be enabled on one host at a time. Currently the service is enabled on all cloud controllers.

This issue also impacts CloudWatch and ELB services which use similar checks to determine if they are enabled:

{code}
  Topology.isEnabledLocally( AutoScaling.class )
{code}

This means that background activities would be attempted multiple times, such as CloudWatch alarm evaluation or attempting to launch an instance in Auto Scaling.

comments.body:
The errors we are seeing are not necessarily related to changes made for this issue, but here's the error that occurs when attempting to use the Auto Scaling service located with the disabled Eucalyptus service:

{code}
# euscale-create-launch-config -i emi-59CB3761 -t m1.small Config2
euscale-create-launch-config: error (ValidationError): Invalid parameters [Unable to validate references at this time.]
{code}

and the related log:

{code}
Thu May 30 21:30:27 2013 ERROR [AsyncRequest:Eucalyptus.eucalyptus:EucalyptusConfiguration:arn:euca:eucalyptus:::10.111.5.8/.class java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor$Worker#263] [com.eucalyptus.util.async.AsyncRequest$2.call(AsyncRequest.java):232] java.lang.RuntimeException: com.eucalyptus.ws.EucalyptusRemoteFault: Action:ProblemAction Code:soapenv:Client Id:RelatesTo Error: No such userNo such user
{code}

It looks like sending messages between hosts is failing. It was expected that services would be enabled on the same host so this usage was not anticipated.

Similar result for ELB:

{code}
[root@clcfrontend admin]# eulb-create-lb -l "lb-port=80, protocol=HTTP, instance-port=80" vic -z one
eulb-create-lb: error (InternalFailure): Unable to verify the requested zones
[root@clcfrontend admin]#
{code}
